{"topicId":"vanishing-points","flashcards":[{"id":"fc-1","front":"What is a vanishing point in perspective projection?","back":"A vanishing point is a point on the horizon where parallel lines that are not parallel to the image plane appear to converge. It is a fundamental element of linear perspective that provides the illusion of depth in a two‑dimensional image."},{"id":"fc-2","front":"Describe one‑point perspective and its typical use.","back":"One‑point perspective has a single vanishing point placed at the centre of the horizon (or at the principal point). All lines that are perpendicular to the view plane converge to this point, while lines parallel to the view plane remain parallel. It is commonly used for interiors, corridors, and railway tracks."},{"id":"fc-3","front":"Explain two‑point perspective, including the arrangement of vanishing points.","back":"In two‑point perspective two vanishing points are placed on the horizon line (the image of the ground plane). Horizontal lines converge toward one of the two points, while vertical lines stay vertical (parallel to the image plane). This setup is typical for rendering a corner of a building or any object viewed from an angle."},{"id":"fc-4","front":"Explain three‑point perspective and when it is employed.","back":"Three‑point perspective adds a third vanishing point not on the horizon: two horizontal vanishing points on the horizon line and a third vertical vanishing point either above (bird’s‑eye view) or below (worm’s‑eye view). Vertical lines converge toward the third point, creating a strong sense of height. It is used for tall structures viewed from above or below."},{"id":"fc-5","front":"How can you calculate a vanishing point from two parallel 3‑D lines?","back":"Given two parallel 3‑D direction vectors d1 and d2 (they are identical), project each direction onto the image plane using the camera’s projection matrix P = K[R|t]. The vanishing point V is the homogeneous coordinates of P·[d;0]. Alternatively, in a pure homography, intersect the two image lines that represent the projections of the parallel 3‑D lines: V = l1 × l2 (cross product). MCQ: Which matrix is used to obtain the vanishing point? (a) Model matrix (b) View matrix (c) Projection matrix (d) Texture matrix. Answer: (c) Projection matrix."},{"id":"fc-6","front":"What role do vanishing points play in the camera projection matrix?","back":"Vanishing points are directly related to the columns of the rotation part of the camera’s extrinsic matrix and the focal length in the intrinsic matrix K. For a direction d, the vanishing point in image coordinates is v = K(R·d + t_zeros). The principal point (cx, cy) in K determines where the horizon (the line connecting the two horizontal vanishing points) is placed."},{"id":"fc-7","front":"Provide a short code snippet (Python) that computes a 2‑point perspective projection of a 3‑D point onto the image plane.","back":"```python\\nimport numpy as np\\n\\ndef project_point(pt, K, R, t, f):\\n    # pt: 3D point (x, y, z)\\n    # K: intrinsic matrix 3x3 (fx, fy, cx, cy)\\n    # R: rotation matrix 3x3\\n    # t: translation vector 3x1\\n    # f: focal length (redundant if K already contains it)\\n    # Convert to camera coordinates\\n    cam_pt = R @ pt + t\\n    # Perspective division\\n    if cam_pt[2] == 0:\\n        return None\\n    x_n = cam_pt[0] / cam_pt[2]\\n    y_n = cam_pt[1] / cam_pt[2]\\n    # Apply intrinsic matrix\\n    img_pt = K @ np.array([x_n, y_n, 1.0])\\n    return img_pt[:2]  # (u, v) pixel coordinates\\n\\n# Example: 2‑point perspective: directions (1,0,0) and (0,0,1) become vanishing points\\nK = np.array([[800, 0, 320],\\n              [0, 800, 240],\\n              [0,   0,   1]])\\nR = np.eye(3)\\nt = np.zeros((3,1))\\n# Direction vectors for the two horizontal axes\\nd1 = np.array([1.0, 0.0, 0.0])\\nd2 = np.array([0.0, 0.0, 1.0])\\n# Compute vanishing points (project direction as point at infinity)\\nvp1 = project_point(d1 * 1000, K, R, t, 800)  # far along X\\nvp2 = project_point(d2 * 1000, K, R, t, 800)  # far along Z\\nprint(\\\"VP1 (u,v):\\\", vp1)\\nprint(\\\"VP2 (u,v):\\\", vp2)\\n```\\nThe code projects direction vectors at infinity, giving the two vanishing points on the horizon."},{"id":"fc-8","front":"MCQ: The image of a tall skyscraper seen from ground level with vertical lines converging upward is an example of which perspective type? (a) One‑point (b) Two‑point (c) Three‑point (d) Zero‑point","back":"Answer: (c) Three‑point perspective. The third vanishing point is above the horizon, causing vertical lines to converge upward."}]}